Using Callisto 1.0

I'm using QueryOutputHelper in a project to run a couple of statements. The number of statements depends. Basically it's an action that executes upgrade scripts found in a specific folder. 

It was pretty easy to get this going. However, there were some problems I had to workaround.

1. I wanted to execute things nicely in a background job but this doesn't work. I had to wrap basically every call to RDB API into a Runnable to be executed in the UI Thread.

2. With every single output the output view is brought to front. I tracked it down to OutputUtil#getOutputView(boolean). The corresponding code snippet is the following.

            //look for the output view. If we find it, then return it.
            for (int i = 0; i < viewReference.length; i++) {
               viewPart = viewReference[i].getView(false);
               if (viewPart instanceof OutputView) {
                  display.syncExec(new Runnable() {
                     public void run() {
                        activePage.bringToTop( viewPart );
                     }
                  });
                  return (OutputView) viewPart;
               }
            }


It would be better if this could be a user preference, i.e. like the console view handled this. Bringing the output view to front for every single message makes Eclipse really unusable for executing hundred or more statements at once.

BTW, what are the official API recommendations for doing this? I followed the org.eclipse.wst.rdb.sqleditor.internal.actions.SQLRunAction implementation with the exception that I don't have an SQL editor but read the content from each script and use it directly.

The relevant line of code is:

defaultLocation = buildURL(new File(FrameworkProperties.getProperty(PROP_USER_DIR), "workspace").getAbsolutePath(), true); //$NON-NLS-1$

The buildUrl method looks like:

        public static URL buildURL(String spec, boolean trailingSlash) {
		if (spec == null)
			return null;
		boolean isFile = spec.startsWith("file:"); //$NON-NLS-1$
		try {
			if (isFile)
				return adjustTrailingSlash(new File(spec.substring(5)).toURL(), trailingSlash);
			else
				return new URL(spec);
		} catch (MalformedURLException e) {
			// if we failed and it is a file spec, there is nothing more we can do
			// otherwise, try to make the spec into a file URL.
			if (isFile)
				return null;
			try {
				return adjustTrailingSlash(new File(spec).toURL(), trailingSlash);
			} catch (MalformedURLException e1) {
				return null;
			}
		}
	}

So the method is expecting something like "file:///C:/Eclipse/Workspace/" but instead, is getting something like "C:/Eclipse/Workspace/", resulting in an MalformedURLException being thrown.

If a java file is deleted by using IFile.delete method from a project in the workspace and immediately same file location is written by using FileOutputStream, then the file in text editor does not updated.

To be more clear, the following results are from my experiences while working on a related bug.

IFile file points to "C:\workspace\myProject\com\ibm\MyFile.java" and this file is opened on eclipse on java editor(it does not matter whether it is focused or not)

IProject project points to the java project named myProject that file (named myFile) is in it.

1. file.delete(true, new NullProgressMonitor());
2. FileOutputStream fos = new FileOutputStream(file);
3. fos.write("blabla");
4. project.refreshLocal(IResource.DEPTH_INFINITE, new NullProgressMonitor()); 

When this code is run, the file on java editor of eclipse remains same. But if 4th line is commented or 2 seconds delay is put after first line, then the file is closed automatically.

If the same process is done manually by using the file system of Windows (basically delete the file and create it again with the same name and write something in it), Eclipse says that the file is updated and whether the user likes to load changes or not.

If first line is commented, then the file is updated by Eclipse without saying anything to user. 


I think the problem occurs when we delete a file, eclipse invokes methods to close the opened file, but since we create it again, it double checks whether file is really deleted and it returns false and does not update file on java editor. I was expecting it to check time stamps of file, but I think they are also deleted when we invoke IFile.delete method. So Eclipse can not compare time stamps and leaves the file as it is.

For Area Chart, beforeDrawDataPoint( ) function does not take effort on the color of series. Instead of that, it only changes the color of data point marker(if any), which is same with Line Chart.

To achieve your expected effect, please use beforeDrawSeries( ) instead. For instance, the script code could be implemented as follows:

function beforeDrawSeries( series, seriesRenderer, context )
{
   importPackage(Packages.org.eclipse.birt.chart.model.data);
   importPackage(Packages.org.eclipse.birt.chart.model.attribute.impl);

   seriesText = series.getSeriesIdentifier();

   if (seriesText == "A") 
   {
     ((SeriesDefinition)(series.eContainer( ))).getSeriesPalette( )
        .update( ColorDefinitionImpl.create(255, 0, 0) );
   }
   else if (seriesText == "B") 
   {
     ((SeriesDefinition)(series.eContainer( ))).getSeriesPalette( )
        .update( ColorDefinitionImpl.create(0, 0, 255));
   }
   else if (seriesText == "C") 
   {
     ((SeriesDefinition)(series.eContainer( ))).getSeriesPalette( )
        .update( ColorDefinitionImpl.create(0, 255, 0));
   } 
   else if (seriesText == "D") 
   {
     ((SeriesDefinition)(series.eContainer( ))).getSeriesPalette( )
        .update( ColorDefinitionImpl.create(255, 255, 0));
   }	
}

Cheers.
